# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-authentication-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] It’s been available across browsers since September 2019.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] The **`CredentialsContainer`** interface of the Credential Management API exposes methods to request credentials and notify the user agent when events such as successful sign in or sign out happen.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] This interface is accessible from `Navigator.credentials`.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with a new `Credential` instance based on the provided options, or `null` if no `Credential` object can be created.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] In exceptional circumstances, the `Promise` may reject.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with the `Credential` instance that matches the provided parameters.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] Sets a flag that specifies whether automatic log in is allowed for future visits to the current origin, then returns an empty `Promise`.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] For example, you might call this, after a user signs out of a website to ensure that they aren't automatically signed in on the next site visit.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] Earlier versions of the spec called this method `requireUserMediation()`.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] See Browser compatibility for support details.
[src:web-authentication-api/credentialscontainer] Stores a set of credentials for a user, inside a provided `Credential` instance and returns that instance in a `Promise`.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The **FIDO** (**Fast IDentity Online**) **Alliance** is an open industry association launched in February 2013 whose stated mission is to develop and promote authentication standards that "help reduce the world’s over-reliance on passwords".
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] FIDO addresses the lack of interoperability among devices that use strong authentication and reduces the problems users face creating and remembering multiple usernames and passwords.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The USB security token device may be used to authenticate using a simple password (e.g. four-digit PIN) or by pressing a button.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The specifications emphasize a device-centric model.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] Authentication over an insecure channel happens using public-key cryptography.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The user's device registers the user to a server by registering a public key.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] To authenticate the user, the device signs a challenge from the server using the private key that it holds.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The keys on the device are unlocked by a local user gesture such as a biometric or pressing a button.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] FIDO provides two types of user experiences depending on which protocol is used.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] Both protocols define a common interface at the client for whatever local authentication method the user exercises.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The following open specifications may be obtained from the FIDO web site.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The U2F 1.0 Proposed Standard (October 9, 2014) was the starting point for the specification known as FIDO 2.0 Proposed Standard (September 4, 2015).
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The latter was formally submitted to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) on November 12, 2015.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] Subsequently, the first Working Draft of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard was published on May 31, 2016.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The WebAuthn standard has been revised numerous times since then, becoming a W3C Recommendation on March 4, 2019.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] Meanwhile the U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (July 11, 2017) became the starting point for the Client to Authenticator Protocol 2.0 Proposed Standard, which was published on September 27, 2017.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] FIDO CTAP 2.0 complements W3C WebAuthn, both of which are in scope for the *FIDO2 Project*.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The FIDO2 Project is a joint effort between the FIDO Alliance and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) whose goal is to create strong authentication for the web.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] At its core, FIDO2 consists of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard and the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol 2 (CTAP2).
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] FIDO2 is based upon previous work done by the FIDO Alliance, in particular the Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) authentication standard.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] Taken together, WebAuthn and CTAP specify a standard authentication protocol where the protocol endpoints consist of a user-controlled cryptographic authenticator (such as a smartphone or a hardware security key) and a WebAuthn Relying Party (also called a FIDO2 server).
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] A web user agent (i.e., a web browser) together with a WebAuthn client form an intermediary between the authenticator and the relying party.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] A single WebAuthn client Device may support multiple WebAuthn clients.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] For example, a laptop may support multiple clients, one for each conforming user agent running on the laptop.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] A conforming user agent implements the WebAuthn JavaScript API.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] As its name implies, the Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) enables a conforming cryptographic authenticator to interoperate with a WebAuthn client.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The CTAP specification refers to two protocol versions called CTAP1/U2F and CTAP2.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] An authenticator that implements one of these protocols is typically referred to as a U2F authenticator or a FIDO2 authenticator, respectively.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] A FIDO2 authenticator that also implements the CTAP1/U2F protocol is backward compatible with U2F.
[src:web-authentication-api/fido2-project] The invention of using a smartphone as a cryptographic authenticator on a computer network is claimed in US patent 7,366,913 filed in 2002.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Usage of MFA has increased in recent years.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Security issues which can cause the bypass of MFA are fatigue attacks, phishing and SIM swapping.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Accounts with MFA enabled are significantly less likely to be compromised.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Authentication takes place when someone tries to log into a computer resource (such as a computer network, device, or application).
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The resource requires the user to supply the identity by which the user is known to the resource, along with evidence of the authenticity of the user's claim to that identity.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Simple authentication requires only one such piece of evidence (factor), typically a password, or occasionally multiple pieces of evidence all of the same type, as with a credit card number and a card verification code (CVC).
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] For additional security, the resource may require more than one factor—multi-factor authentication, or two-factor authentication in cases where exactly two types of evidence are to be supplied.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The use of multiple authentication factors to prove one's identity is based on the premise that an unauthorized actor is unlikely to be able to supply all of the factors required for access.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] If, in an authentication attempt, at least one of the components is missing or supplied incorrectly, the user's identity is not established with sufficient certainty and access to the asset (e.g., a building, or data) being protected by multi-factor authentication then remains blocked.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] An example of two-factor authentication is the withdrawing of money from an ATM; only the correct combination of a physically present bank card (something the user possesses) and a PIN (something the user knows) allows the transaction to be carried out.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Two other examples are to supplement a user-controlled password with a one-time password (OTP) or code generated or received by an authenticator (e.g. a security token or smartphone) that only the user possesses.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] An authenticator app enables two-factor authentication in a different way, by showing a randomly generated and constantly refreshing code, rather than sending an SMS or using another method.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] This code is a Time-based one-time password (a *TOTP*), and the authenticator app contains the key material that allows the generation of these codes.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Knowledge factors ("something only the user knows") are a form of authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In this form, the user is required to prove knowledge of a secret in order to authenticate.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] A password is a secret word or string of characters that is used for user authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] This is the most commonly used mechanism of authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication techniques rely on passwords as one factor of authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Variations include both longer ones formed from multiple words (a passphrase) and the shorter, purely numeric, PIN commonly used for ATM access.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Traditionally, passwords are expected to be memorized, but can also be written down on a hidden paper or text file.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Possession factors ("something only the user has") have been used for authentication for centuries, in the form of a key to a lock.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The basic principle is that the key embodies a secret that is shared between the lock and the key, and the same principle underlies possession factor authentication in computer systems.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] A security token is an example of a possession factor.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] *soft token*) is a type of two-factor authentication security device that may be used to authorize the use of computer services.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] A soft token may not be a device the user interacts with.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Typically an X.509v3 certificate is loaded onto the device and stored securely to serve this purpose.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Inherent factors ("something the user is"), are factors associated with the user, and are usually biometric methods, including fingerprint, face, voice, or iris recognition.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Behavioral biometrics such as keystroke dynamics can also be used.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Increasingly, a fourth factor is coming into play involving the physical location of the user.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] While hard wired to the corporate network, a user could be allowed to login using only a pin code, whereas if the user was working remotely, a more secure MFA method such as entering a code from a soft token as well could be required.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Adapting the type of MFA method and frequency to a users' location will enable the avoidance of risks common to remote working.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Systems for network admission control work in similar ways where the level of network access can be contingent on the specific network a device is connected to, such as Wi-Fi vs wired connectivity.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] This also allows a user to move between offices and dynamically receive the same level of network access in each.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Two-factor authentication over text message was developed as early as 1996, when AT&T described a system for authorizing transactions based on an exchange of codes over two-way pagers.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication vendors offer mobile phone-based authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Some methods include push-based authentication, QR code-based authentication, one-time password authentication (event-based and time-based), and SMS-based verification.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] SMS-based verification suffers from some security concerns.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Phones can be cloned, apps can run on several phones and cell-phone maintenance personnel can read SMS texts.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Not least, cell phones can be compromised in general, meaning the phone is no longer something only the user has.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The major drawback of authentication including something the user possesses is that the user must carry around the physical token (the USB stick, the bank card, the key or similar), practically at all times.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Many organizations forbid carrying USB and electronic devices in or out of premises owing to malware and data theft risks, and most important machines do not have USB ports for the same reason.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Physical tokens usually do not scale, typically requiring a new token for each new account and system.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Procuring and subsequently replacing tokens of this kind involves costs.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In addition, there are inherent conflicts and unavoidable trade-offs between usability and security.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Two-step authentication involving mobile phones and smartphones provides an alternative to dedicated physical devices.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] To authenticate, people can use their personal access codes to the device (i.e. something that only the individual user knows) plus a one-time-valid, dynamic passcode, typically consisting of 4 to 6 digits.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The passcode can be sent to their mobile device by SMS or can be generated by a one-time passcode-generator app.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In both cases, the advantage of using a mobile phone is that there is no need for an additional dedicated token, as users tend to carry their mobile devices around at all times.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Notwithstanding the popularity of SMS verification, security advocates have publicly criticized SMS verification, and in July 2016, a United States NIST draft guideline proposed deprecating it as a form of authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] A year later NIST reinstated SMS verification as a valid authentication channel in the finalized guideline.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] As early as 2011, Duo Security was offering push notifications for MFA via a mobile app.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In 2016 and 2017 respectively, both Google and Apple started offering user two-step authentication with push notifications as an alternative method.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Security of SMS-delivered security tokens fully depends on the mobile operator's operational security and can be easily breached by wiretapping or SIM cloning by national security agencies.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The Payment Card Industry (PCI) Data Security Standard, requirement 8.3, requires the use of MFA for all remote network access that originates from outside the network to a Card Data Environment (CDE).
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Beginning with PCI-DSS version 3.2, the use of MFA is required for all administrative access to the CDE, even if the user is within a trusted network.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The second Payment Services Directive requires "strong customer authentication" on most electronic payments in the European Economic Area since September 14, 2019.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In India, the Reserve Bank of India mandated two-factor authentication for all online transactions made using a debit or credit card using either a password or a one-time password sent over SMS.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] This requirement was removed in 2016 for transactions up to ₹2,000 after opting-in with the issuing bank.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Vendors such as Uber have been mandated by the bank to amend their payment processing systems in compliance with this two-factor authentication rollout.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Details for authentication for federal employees and contractors in the U.S. are defined in Homeland Security Presidential Directive 12 (HSPD-12).
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] IT regulatory standards for access to federal government systems require the use of multi-factor authentication to access sensitive IT resources, for example when logging on to network devices to perform administrative tasks and when accessing any computer using a privileged login.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] NIST Special Publication 800-63-3 discusses various forms of two-factor authentication and provides guidance on using them in business processes requiring different levels of assurance.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In response to the publication, numerous authentication vendors began improperly promoting challenge-questions, secret images, and other knowledge-based methods as "multi-factor" authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Considering the reliability of the method, in some countries, MFA is obligatory in certain industries, such as healthcare, to prevent the theft of sensitive information.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In the healthcare sector, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule has historically listed access controls as a required implementation specification but did not explicitly mandate multi-factor authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The HHS Office for Civil Rights noted in enforcement guidance that the lack of MFA was a contributing factor in multiple healthcare data breaches investigated under HIPAA.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In December 2024, HHS published a Notice of Proposed Rulemaking that would make multi-factor authentication a mandatory requirement for all HIPAA-regulated entities accessing electronic protected health information.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] According to proponents, multi-factor authentication could drastically reduce the incidence of online identity theft and other online fraud, because the victim's password would no longer be enough to give a thief permanent access to their information.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] However, many multi-factor authentication approaches remain vulnerable to phishing, man-in-the-browser, and man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] To counter phishing attacks, users should not share their verification codes with anyone, and many web application providers will place an advisory in an e-mail or SMS containing a code.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In May 2017, O2 Telefónica, a German mobile service provider, confirmed that cybercriminals had exploited SS7 vulnerabilities to bypass SMS based two-step authentication to do unauthorized withdrawals from users' bank accounts.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] The criminals first infected the account holder's computers in an attempt to steal their bank account credentials and phone numbers.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Then the attackers purchased access to a fake telecom provider and set up a redirect for the victim's phone number to a handset controlled by them.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Finally, the attackers logged into victims' online bank accounts and requested for the money on the accounts to be withdrawn to accounts owned by the criminals.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] SMS passcodes were routed to phone numbers controlled by the attackers and the criminals transferred the money out.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] An increasingly common approach to defeating MFA is to bombard the user with many requests to accept a log-in, until the user eventually succumbs to the volume of requests and by mistake accepts one.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] This form of social engineering is called *multi-factor authentication fatigue attack* (also MFA fatigue attack or MFA bombing), and may include other elements, such as calls pretending to be from IT support.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] When MFA applications are configured to send push notifications to end users, an attacker can send a flood of login attempts in the hope that a user will click on accept at least once.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In 2022, Microsoft deployed a mitigation against MFA fatigue attacks with their authenticator app, by optionally requiring the user to type in a number in addition to clicking "approve".
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In September 2022 Uber security was breached by a member of Lapsus$ using a multi-factor fatigue attack.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In early 2024, a small percentage of Apple consumers experienced a MFA fatigue attack that was caused by a hacker that bypassed the rate limit and Captcha on Apple’s “Forgot Password” page.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Many multi-factor authentication products require users to deploy client software to make multi-factor authentication systems work.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Some vendors have created separate installation packages for network login, Web access credentials, and VPN connection credentials.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] For such products, there may be four or five different software packages to push down to the client PC in order to make use of the token or smart card.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] This translates to four or five packages on which version control has to be performed, and four or five packages to check for conflicts with business applications.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] If access can be operated using web pages, it is possible to limit the overheads outlined above to a single application.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] With other multi-factor authentication technology such as hardware token products, no software must be installed by end-users.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Some studies have shown that poorly implemented MFA recovery procedures can introduce new vulnerabilities that attackers may exploit.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] There are drawbacks to multi-factor authentication that are keeping many approaches from becoming widespread.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Some users have difficulty keeping track of a hardware token or USB plug.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Many users do not have the technical skills needed to install a client-side software certificate by themselves.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Generally, multi-factor solutions require additional investment for implementation and costs for maintenance.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Most hardware token-based systems are proprietary, and some vendors charge an annual fee per user.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Deployment of hardware tokens is logistically challenging.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Hardware tokens may get damaged or lost, and issuance of tokens in large industries such as banking or even within large enterprises needs to be managed.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In addition to deployment costs, multi-factor authentication often carries significant additional support costs.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] A 2008 survey of over 120 U.S. credit unions by the *Credit Union Journal* reported on the support costs associated with two-factor authentication.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In their report, software certificates and software toolbar approaches were reported to have the highest support costs.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] Research into deployments of multi-factor authentication schemes has shown that one of the elements that tend to impact the adoption of such systems is the line of business of the organization that deploys the multi-factor authentication system.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] While the perception is that multi-factor authentication is within the realm of perfect security, Roger Grimes writes that if not properly implemented and configured, multi-factor authentication can in fact be easily defeated.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] In 2013, Kim Dotcom claimed to have invented two-factor authentication in a 2000 patent, and briefly threatened to sue all the major web services.
[src:web-authentication-api/multi-factor-authentication] However, the European Patent Office revoked his patent in light of an earlier 1998 U.S. patent held by AT&T.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] It’s been available across browsers since September 2021.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] The **`PublicKeyCredential`** interface provides information about a public key / private key pair, which is a credential for logging in to a service using an un-phishable and data-breach resistant asymmetric key pair instead of a password.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] It inherits from `Credential`, and is part of the Web Authentication API extension to the Credential Management API.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] A string that indicates the mechanism by which the WebAuthn implementation is attached to the authenticator at the time the associated `navigator.credentials.create()` or `navigator.credentials.get()` call completes.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Inherited from `Credential` and overridden to be the base64url encoding of `PublicKeyCredential.rawId`.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] An `ArrayBuffer` that holds the globally unique identifier for this `PublicKeyCredential`.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] This identifier can be used to look up credentials for future calls to `navigator.credentials.get()`.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] An instance of an `AuthenticatorResponse` object.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] It is either of type `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse` if the `PublicKeyCredential` was the results of a `navigator.credentials.create()` call, or of type `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` if the `PublicKeyCredential` was the result of a `navigator.credentials.get()` call.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Always set to `public-key` for `PublicKeyCredential` instances.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an object that can be used to check whether or not particular WebAuthn capabilities and extensions are supported.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Returns a `Promise` which resolves to `true` if conditional mediation is available.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Returns a `Promise` which resolves to `true` if an authenticator bound to the platform is capable of *verifying* the user.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Convenience method for deserializing server-sent credential registration data when registering a user with credentials.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Convenience method for deserializing server-sent credential request data when authenticating a (registered) user.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Signals to the authenticator all of the valid credential IDs that the relying party server still holds for a particular user.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Signals to the authenticator that a particular user has updated their user name and/or display name.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Signals to the authenticator that a credential ID was not recognized by the relying party server, for example because it was deleted.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] If any extensions were requested, this method will return the results of processing those extensions.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Convenience method for creating a JSON string representation of a `PublicKeyCredential` for sending to the server when registering a user with credentials and authenticating a registered user.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Here, we use `navigator.credentials.create()` to generate a new credential.
[src:web-authentication-api/publickeycredential] Here, we fetch an existing credential from an authenticator, using `navigator.credentials.get()`.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The Web Authentication API (WebAuthn) is an extension of the Credential Management API that enables strong authentication with public key cryptography, enabling passwordless authentication and secure multi-factor authentication (MFA) without SMS texts.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] On the web, passkeys are implemented using the Web Authentication API.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] WebAuthn uses asymmetric (public-key) cryptography instead of passwords or SMS texts for registering, authenticating, and multi-factor authentication with websites.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Many websites already have pages that allow users to register new accounts or log into an existing account, and WebAuthn acts as a replacement or enhancement for the authentication part of the system.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] In their most basic forms, both `create()` and `get()` receive a very large random number called the "challenge" from the server and return the challenge signed by the private key back to the server.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This proves to the server that a user has the private key required for authentication without revealing any secrets over the network.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The web app initiates generation of a new credential via the authenticator, on behalf of the relying party, via a `navigator.credentials.create()` call.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This call is passed a `publicKey` option specifying device capabilities, e.g., whether the device provides its own user authentication (for example with biometrics).
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] After the authenticator obtains user consent, it generates a key pair and returns the public key and optional signed attestation to the web app.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This is provided when the `Promise` returned by the `create()` call fulfills, in the form of a `PublicKeyCredential` object instance (the `PublicKeyCredential.response` property contains the attestation information).
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The web app forwards the `PublicKeyCredential` to the relying party server, again using an appropriate mechanism.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The relying party server stores the public key, coupled with the user identity, to remember the credential for future authentications.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] During this process, it performs a series of checks to ensure that the registration was complete and not tampered with.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Ensuring that the origin was the origin expected.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Validating that the signature and attestation are using the correct certificate chain for the specific model of the authenticator used to generate the key pair in the first place.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] After a user has registered with WebAuthn, they can authenticate (login) with the service.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Creates an assertion using the previously-generated key pair for the service, rather than the authenticator's key pair.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The browser asks the authenticator to sign the challenge via a `navigator.credentials.get()` call, which is passed the credentials in a `publicKey` option.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] If the authenticator contains one of the given credentials and is able to successfully sign the challenge, it returns a signed assertion to the web app after receiving user consent.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This is provided when the `Promise` returned by the `get()` call fulfills, in the form of a `PublicKeyCredential` object instance (the `PublicKeyCredential.response` property contains the assertion information).
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The web app forwards the signed assertion to the relying party server for the relying party to validate.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Ensuring that the challenge that was signed by the authenticator matches the challenge that was generated by the server.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Checking that the Relying Party ID is the one expected for this service.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Once verified by the server, the authentication flow is considered successful.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] With non-discoverable credentials, the private key material, as well as additional information such as the username and the ID of the RP, are stored outside the authenticator, typically in the RP server (which is why these credentials are also sometimes called *server-side credentials*).
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] To keep the private key safe in the server, it is encrypted using a master key that is stored in the authenticator, and the resulting ciphertext is used as the credential ID.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Encrypts the private key and other data with a master key stored in the authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Returns the resulting ciphertext to the RP as the new credential's `id`, along with the rest of the credential, such as the public key.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The authenticator decrypts the credential ID value into the private key and other data, using the authenticator's stored master key.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The authenticator uses the private key to sign an assertion.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The advantage of a non-discoverable credential is that the authenticator doesn't have to store any credential-specific data, and this means it could support an essentially infinite number of credentials.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The disadvantage is that to use a non-discoverable credential, the user must first supply the username they want to sign in as, which the RP can then use to find a set of corresponding credential ID values, which the browser can provide to the authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This is the foundation of the autofill UI feature.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Use the `residentKey` option in `PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions` to control whether a new public key credential will be discoverable or non-discoverable.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Autofill UI, also sometimes called *conditional mediation*, is a feature that makes it easier for users to work with public key credentials, especially when they also have passwords for the site.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] It's expected that websites that adopt passkeys will typically add them alongside existing support for password-based authentication, so a user might, for a given site, have a password, one or more passkeys, or both.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] In this situation, a UI that asks them which method they want to sign in with can be confusing: they might not remember which method they have for which account.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Autofill UI helps with this problem, by inviting users to sign in with a passkey if and only if a suitable passkey is currently available.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] To enable autofill UI, the website's sign-in page contains a form, which invites them to sign in.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] When the page loads, the website first checks that conditional mediation is supported, and if it is, makes a call to `CredentialsContainer.get()`.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This will wait until the user has interacted with the username field.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] If and when the user does interact with the field, the browser will ask any available authenticators for public key credentials that can be used to sign into this website, and display the associated usernames as autofill options for the user, alongside any saved passwords for the account.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] If the user selects one of these options, the browser will use that credential to sign the user in.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This essentially enables a website to provide a unified autofill, including both passwords and public key credentials for a single account.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] It is possible for the information stored in a user's authenticator about a discoverable credential to go out sync with the relying party's server.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] This might happen when the user deletes a credential or modifies their user/display name on the RP web app without updating the authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] It may seem like `signalUnknownCredential()` and `signalAllAcceptedCredentials()` have similar purposes, so what situation should each one be used in?
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The signup and login workflows can be customized based on the capabilities of the WebAuthn client (browser).
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The `PublicKeyCredential.getClientCapabilities()` static method can be used to query those capabilities; it returns an object where each key refers to a WebAuthn capability or extension, and each value is a boolean indicating support for that feature.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The code below shows how you might use `getClientCapabilities()` to check if the client supports authenticators that offer biometric user verification.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Note that the actual actions performed depend on your site.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] For sites that *require* biometric authentication, you might replace the login UI with a message indicating that biometric authentication is needed, and the user should try a different browser or device.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Both directives have a default allowlist value of `"self"`, meaning that by default these methods can be used in top-level document contexts.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] In addition, `get()` can be used in nested browsing contexts loaded from the same origin as the top-most document.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] `get()` and `create()` can be used in nested browsing contexts loaded from the different origins to the top-most document (i.e., in cross-origin `<iframes>`), if allowed by the `publickey-credentials-get` and `publickey-credentials-create` `Permissions-Policy` directives, respectively.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] For cross-origin `create()` calls, where the permission was granted by `allow=` on an iframe, the frame must also have Transient activation.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Provides proof to a service that an authenticator has the necessary key pair to successfully handle an authentication request initiated by a `CredentialsContainer.get()` call.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Available in the `response` property of the `PublicKeyCredential` instance obtained when the `get()` `Promise` fulfills.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The result of a WebAuthn credential registration (i.e., a `CredentialsContainer.create()` call).
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] It contains information about the credential that the server needs to perform WebAuthn assertions, such as its credential ID and public key.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Available in the `response` property of the `PublicKeyCredential` instance obtained when the `create()` `Promise` fulfills.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] The base interface for `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse` and `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse`.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Provides information about a public key / private key pair, which is a credential for logging into a service using an un-phishable and data-breach resistant asymmetric key pair instead of a password.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Obtained when the `Promise` returned via a `create()` or `get()` call fulfills.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Calling `create()` with a `publicKey` option initiates the creation of new asymmetric key credentials via an authenticator, as explained above.
[src:web-authentication-api/web-authentication-api] Calling `get()` with a `publicKey` option instructs the user agent uses an existing set of credentials to authenticate to a relying party.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] To use WebAuthn, users require a compatible authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The standard does not specify how to store the keys required for signing, so a variety of authenticator types can be used.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The most common authenticator type is a platform authenticator, which is built into the operating system of the device.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Common platform authenticators include Android, Apple Keychain and Windows Hello.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] These make use of hardware security features (such as TEE and TPM), and often sync credentials between devices for ease-of-use.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Another common authenticator type is a roaming authenticator, where a separate hardware device authenticates the user by connecting over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Most smartphones can be used as roaming authenticators, and dedicated physical security keys are also used.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] WebAuthn is effectively backward compatible with FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) as they both use the CTAP protocol.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Password managers can also be used as an authenticator, often with cloud sync.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Where credentials sync is not viable or possible, WebAuthn Hybrid Transport can be used to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Like legacy U2F, WebAuthn is resistant to some phishing attacks as the authenticator only offers credentials that were registered on the same website.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] However, unlike U2F, WebAuthn can be implemented in a passwordless manner.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Moreover, a roaming hardware authenticator resists malware, since the keys are stored on a separate device, which prevents the malware from accessing them directly.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 and 2 standards were published as W3C Recommendations on 4 March 2019 and 8 April 2021 respectively.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] A Level 3 specification is currently a *First Public Working Draft* (FPWD).
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] WebAuthn is a core component of the FIDO2 Project under the guidance of the FIDO Alliance.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] FIDO2 is the successor to FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F).
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Whereas U2F only supports multi-factor mode, having been designed to strengthen existing username/password-based login flows, FIDO2 adds support for single-factor mode.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] In multi-factor mode, the authenticator is activated by a test of *user presence*, which usually consists of a simple button push; no password is required.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] In single-factor mode, the authenticator (*something you have*) performs *user verification*.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Regardless of mode, the authenticator never shares its secrets or biometric data with the website.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Moreover, a single user's secret or biometric works with all websites, as the authenticator selects the correct cryptographic key material to use for the service requesting authentication after user verification was completed successfully.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] A secret and biometric on the authenticator can be used together, similarly to how they would be used on a smartphone.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] For example, a fingerprint provides convenient access to user's smartphone, but occasionally fingerprint access fails, in which case user can use a PIN.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] When Apple first introduced passkeys to the public in 2022, they emphasized their first-party platform integrations.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] This, combined with the lack of clear communication from other industry leaders, led some to speculate that passkeys were proprietary to Apple, which was not the case.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] As browsers and websites began to implement WebAuthn, the inconsistent feature-sets resulted in a variety of understandings of what exactly counted as a passkey.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Some people assumed that a passkey required management by a platform authenticator, or needed synchronization using the cloud.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] A better definition is that a passkey is any WebAuthn credential managed by any WebAuthn authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] This definition covers most of what different vendors refer to and accept as *passkeys*.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] WebAuthn specifies how a claimant demonstrates possession and control of a FIDO2 authenticator to a verifier called the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The authentication process is mediated by an entity called the WebAuthn Client, which is little more than a conforming web browser.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Authenticator is a multi-factor cryptographic authenticator that uses public-key cryptography to sign an authentication assertion targeted at the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Assuming the authenticator uses either a facial recognition, fingerprint or PIN for user verification, the authenticator itself is *something you have* while the facial recognition and fingerprint (biometric) are *something you are* and the PIN is *something you know*.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] To initiate the WebAuthn authentication flow, the WebAuthn Relying Party indicates its intentions to the WebAuthn Client (i.e., the browser) via JavaScript.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The WebAuthn Client communicates with the authenticator using a JavaScript API implemented in the browser.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] A roaming authenticator conforms to the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP), and connected over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] WebAuthn does not strictly require a roaming hardware authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Alternatively, a software authenticator (e.g., implemented on a smartphone) or a platform authenticator (i.e., an authenticator implemented directly on the WebAuthn Client Device) may be used.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Relevant examples of platform authenticators include Windows Hello and the Android operating system.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] WebAuthn Hybrid Transport allows the WebAuthn Client to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone, useful in certain situations where credential sync is not viable.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] There is a lingering misunderstanding among users that biometric data is transmitted over the network in the same manner as passwords, which is not the case.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] When the WebAuthn Relying Party receives the signed authentication assertion from the browser, the digital signature on the assertion is verified using a trusted public key for the user.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] To obtain a public key for the user, the WebAuthn Relying Party initiates a WebAuthn registration flow that is similar to the authentication flow illustrated above.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The primary difference is that the authenticator now signs an attestation statement with its attestation private key.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The signed attestation statement contains a copy of the public key that the WebAuthn Relying Party ultimately uses to verify a signed authentication assertion.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The attestation certificate contains metadata describing the authenticator itself.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The digital signature on the attestation statement is verified with the trusted attestation public key for that particular model of authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] How the WebAuthn Relying Party obtains its store of trusted attestation public keys is unspecified.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] One option is to use the FIDO metadata service.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The attestation type specified in the JavaScript determines the trust model.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] For instance, an attestation type called self-attestation may be desired, for which the trust model is essentially trust on first use.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 standard was published as a W3C Recommendation by the Web Authentication Working Group on 4 March 2019.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] WebAuthn is supported by Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari and Opera.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The desktop version of Google Chrome has supported WebAuthn since version 67.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Firefox, which had not fully supported the previous FIDO U2F standard, included and enabled WebAuthn in Firefox version 60, released on 9 May 2018.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] An early Windows Insider release of Microsoft Edge (Build 17682) implemented a version of WebAuthn that works with both Windows Hello as well as external security keys.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Existing FIDO U2F security keys are largely compatible with the WebAuthn standard, though WebAuthn added the ability to reference a unique per-account "user handle" identifier, which older authenticators are unable to store.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] One of the first FIDO2-compatible authenticators was the second-generation Security Key by Yubico, announced on 10 April 2018.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The first FIDO2-compatible authenticators with a display was Trezor Model T by SatoshiLabs, announced on 6 November 2019.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Trezor Model T was also the first authenticator that allowed users to select which FIDO2 resident credential should be used directly on a device.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The first Security Level 2 certified FIDO2 key, called "Goldengate" was announced one year later by eWBM on 8 April 2019.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Dropbox announced support for WebAuthn logins (as a 2nd factor) on 8 May 2018.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Apple announced that Face ID or Touch ID could be used as a WebAuthn platform authenticator with Safari on 24 June 2020.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Several password managers such as Bitwarden and Dashlane support WebAuthn.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] WebAuthn implements an extension of the W3C's more general Credential Management API, which is an attempt to formalize the interaction between websites and web browsers when exchanging user credentials.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The Web Authentication API extends the Credential Management `navigator.credentials.create()` and `navigator.credentials.get()` JavaScript methods so they accept a `publicKey` parameter.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] To check if a browser supports WebAuthn, scripts should check if the `window.PublicKeyCredential` interface is defined.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] In addition to `PublicKeyCredential`, the standard also defines the `AuthenticatorResponse`, `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse`, and `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` interfaces in addition to a variety of dictionaries and other datatypes.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] The API does not allow direct access to or manipulation of private keys, beyond requesting their initial creation.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] In August 2018, Paragon Initiative Enterprises conducted a security audit of the WebAuthn standard.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] While they could not find any specific exploits, they revealed some serious weaknesses in the way the underlying cryptography is used and mandated by the standard.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Paragon Initiative Enterprises also criticized how the standard was initially developed, as the proposal was not made public in advance and experienced cryptographers were not asked for suggestions and feedback.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Hence the standard was not subject to broad cryptographic research from the academic world.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Despite these shortcomings, Paragon Initiative Enterprises still encourage users to continue to use WebAuthn but have come up with some recommendations for potential implementers and developers of the standard that they hope can be implemented before the standard is finalized.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Avoiding such mistakes as early as possible would protect the industry from any challenges that are introduced by broken standards and the need for backwards compatibility.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] ECDAA was only designed to use in combination with device attestation.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] This particular feature of WebAuthn is not necessarily required for authentication to work.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Current implementations allow the user to decide whether an attestation statement is sent during the registration ceremony.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] Independently, relying parties can choose to require attestation or not.
[src:web-authentication-api/webauthn] ECDAA was removed from WebAuthn Level 2 as it was not implemented by browsers nor relying parties.
